anufacturer recommends that patients taking mipomersen not consume more than one alcoholic drink per day. Patients should be advised to seek medical attention if they experience potential signs and symptoms of hepatotoxicity such as fever, rash, itching, anorexia, nausea, vomiting, fatigue, malaise, right upper quadrant pain, dark urine, pale stools, and jaundice.', 'Synergism', 'Gemfibrozil, Fenofibric acid, Evinacumab, Evolocumab, Probucol, Dextrothyroxine, Cholestyramine, Ezetimibe, Clofibrate, Colestipol, Niacin, More', 'Pertuzumab, Olaparib, Rucaparib, Tisagenlecleucel, Aminolevulinic acid, Omacetaxine mepesuccinate, Tazemetostat, Altretamine, Enasidenib, Belzutifan, Mitotane, More', 'Major', NULL, 'DDInter', 'pharmacodynamic', NULL, 'https://ddinter2.scbdd.com/server/interact/122006/', '[1] "Product Information. Kynamro (mipomersen)." Genzyme Corporation, Cambridge, MA.[2] "Product Information. Kynamro (mipomersen)." Genzyme Corporation, Cambridge, MA.', 1767369485);
